@node Progs
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  Blitz Basic has the following commands for programming the voice:

    @{fg shine}SetVoice@{fg text} rate,pitch,mode,sex,volume
    @{fg shine}Speak@{fg text} text$
    @{fg shine}Translate$@{fg text}(text$)
    @{fg shine}PhoneticSpeak@{fg text}(translated$)

  @{fg shine}SetVoice@{fg text}
  This is used for the V36 settings only, and will work with either
  version of the translator.library/narrator.device.

  @{fg shine}Speak@{fg text}
  Will speak the sentence in text$.

  @{fg shine}Translate$@{fg text}
  Will send text$ to the translator.library, and return the phonetic
  version that can be passed to the narrator.device.

  @{fg shine}PhoneticSpeak@{fg text}
  Will send the translated, phonetic$ to the narrator.device.

  If you want to access the V37 features of Amiga speech, you need to
  first create a NewType as follows:

    @{fg shine}NEWTYPE@{fg text}.newvoice

     flags.b        ; 1 to access these features or 0 to ignore them
     F0enthusiasm.b ; pitch difference 0 ~ 255  Default=32
     F0perturb.b    ; wurble in voice  0 ~ 255  Default=0
     F1adj.b        ; F1 pitch  (low)  +/- 100  Default=0
     F2adj.b        ; F2 pitch  (mid)  +/- 100  Default=0
     F3adj.b        ; F3 pitch  (hi)   +/- 100  Default=0
     A1adj.b        ; amplitude (low) -31 ~ 32  Default=0
     A2adj.b        ; amplitude (mid) -31 ~ 32  Default=0
     A3adj.b        ; amplitude (hi)  -31 ~ 32  Default=0
     articulate.b   ; emphasis         0 ~ 255  Default=100
     centralize.b   ; centralization   0 ~ 100  Default=0
     *centphon      ; must be  IY IH EH AE AA AH AO OW UH ER or UW
     AVbias.b       ; AV bias         -31 ~ 32  Default=0
     AFbias.b       ; AF bias         -31 ~ 32  Default=0
     priority.b     ; Priority while speaking   Default=100
     pad1.b         ; just for alignment

    @{fg shine}End NEWTYPE@{fg text}

  Note that these are UBYTEs, and that Talk2Me saves these values
  as words, as Blitz doesn't have a UBYTE - I know that you can
  use AND $FF to get the right value, but I had a reason for
  using words - you can still assign the values to bytes though.

  flags
  The narrator.device will only use the V36 features if this is set
  to 0.

  F0enthusiasm to articulate
  Effect the voice as can be tested with Talk2Me

  Centralize
  Defines how much effect, if any, the *centphon setting has on the
  way that the voice speaks

  *centphon
  should be a pointer to a string, and the string should contain one
  of the valid vowel sounds as shown above.  Talk2Me actually saves
  this value as a word, containing the index of the vowel, so it
  would be best to DIM a set of strings containing the vowel sounds,
  and then have a Centphon$ that gets set to one of them according
  to the index.

  AFbias/AVbias
  Effect the voice as shown with Talk2Me

  There are also other fields in the NewVoice type, but they cannot
  be accessed directly with the Blitz commands - one of the most
  useful of these would be the channelmask, and one that tells the
  narrator.device what to do if only certain channels are available.
  There is also a command to halt speech and flush the buffer, but
  again, this cannot be accessed with the Blitz commands.

  In order to alter the V37 settings, you need to have a pointer, of
  the NewVoice type which points to the VoiceLoc, and you can achieve
  this as follows:

    *nar.newvoice=VoiceLoc

  You can now alter the values in the newvoice structure - this sets
  them to the default values.

    *nar\flags=1
    *nar\F0enthusiasm=32
    *nar\F0perturb=0
    *nar\F1adj=0
    *nar\F2adj=0
    *nar\F3adj=0
    *nar\A1adj=0
    *nar\A2adj=0
    *nar\A3adj=0
    *nar\articulate=100
    *nar\centralize=0
    *nar\centphon=&centphon$    ;the address of the string
                                ;containing the vowel sound.
    *nar\AVbias=0
    *nar\AFbias=0

  I think that's everything you need to know.

 @{fg shine}@{"Right oh..." link MAIN}@{fg text}
@endnode

