@node Notes
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}"NOTES"@{fg text}

  1 The program should detect whether it is running on a PAL or NTSC
    Amiga, and adjust the size of the 'sentences listview' accordingly.
    More sentences are displayed on a PAL system, natch.  Also, the
    Delete Phrase gadget is next to the Search-string gadget on an
    NTSC machine, but is at the bottom on a PAL screen, so NTSC users
    should take care not to press it by mistake.

  2 If you don't have V37+ of the translator.library, then the V37
    gadgets will be disabled.  If you don't have any version of the
    translator.library, the program will probably crash - I've tried
    everything I can to avoid this, but to no avail.  OpenLibrary
    works perfectly in telling me whether it's opened V36 or V37, but
    it crashes whenever I temporarily rename the library.  So make
    sure you've got a version of the translator.library, and the
    narrator.device.

  3 The V36 default settings are of my own choosing, and are the same
    as those that I used for Mr. Wolf (cheeky speaking-clock).  The
    V37 default settings are the 'actual' default settings.  If no
    voices are loaded, then anything spoken, will be with these
    settings.

  4 I cannot access the #CMD_FLUSH command in the narrator.device, so
    there is no way within the program to halt speech - this is why there
    is a checkbox to switch on/off automatic-speech.  This checkmark will
    be disabled if the RATE for a voice is set below 160 - as this affects
    'spoken words per minute' - and it can take a long time to speak some
    sentences.  You can re-check auto while the rate is below 160, if you
    wish.

  5 There are no keyboard-shortcuts for the Menu.  This is because I
    consider that the 'sentence' string gadgets should be activated at all
    times, as this allows for quickly editing and trying new versions of
    a sentence, in order to get it sounding right - unfortunately, this
    means that any attempts to use keyboard-shortcuts for loading/quitting
    etc, would simply be read by the string gadget.  This is one reason for
    adding a pop-up menu.

  6 The ".voices" suffix will be added to any 'voice' files that you save,
    unless the filename already ends this way.

    The ".phrases" suffix will be added to any 'phrase' files that you
    save, unless the filename already ends this way.

    There should be an example file with this archive called

      example.phrases

    The example.phrases file gives you some clues as to how to get
    sentences stressed in the way you want.  Just load the file, and
    then click on each sentence to hear it spoken in the default voice.

  7 In order to hear any changes that you might make to the translated
    sentence - make sure that MODE is set to MANUAL.

  8 Translated sentences that are sent direct to the narrator.device
    MUST end with a space, followed by a null character (0).  DO NOT
    delete the space at the end of the translated strings.  When these
    sentences are saved as .phrases, the space and null character are
    also saved, but if you export them as data statements, then they
    are deleted, as the null character will not appear in the data
    statements, and it is assumed that you will add these characters
    before sending the sentence to the narrator.device.  If you are
    not using the MANUAL option in you program, then you don't need
    to worry about this.

  9 Contact me if you have any problems/suggestions, as this guide
    assumes a certain amount of knowledge about Amiga speech.
    e-mail me: zalda@home4968.freeserve.co.uk

 10 WARNING: I sometimes get crashes if I put a 0 in the last word in
    a sentence.

 @{fg shine}@{"So they're the notes..." link MAIN}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Tips
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}"TIPS"@{fg text}

  Since I added the 'Manual' option, these tips are of slightly less
  value, however, I still think that it is best to get the 'human'
  version of the sentence sounding as good as possible, before
  altering the 'translated' phrase directly.  When you do alter the
  translated phrase, you can put the digits 0-9 after any vowel sounds
  to state how they should be stressed, 0 being low, and 9 being high.
  The translation will probably already have some digits in it, which
  you can change, but you can also add digits after any vowel sounds
  that don't currently have one.

  So, "Hello." would be translated as

    /HEH4LOW.

  and you can change the 4 to another number or delete it, and you can
  add a digit afer OW - so

    /HEH4LOW7.

  sounds much better, as the OW sound is elongated.  Though please note
  that translations have a space at the end of them, which you should NOT
  delete - the program then adds a null character before sending it to
  the narrator.

  Also note that your input is not checked, and that I sometimes get
  crashes if I put a 0 in the last word in a translated string, though
  using 0s seems pretty pointless anyway.

  You can load the example.phrases into Talk2Me, to see ways of achieving
  various types of inflection.  Some sentences have a few versions in
  order to show you how to stress particular words in particular ways.

  You should consider that listening to the voices whilst looking at a
  screen full of information about the voice's settings, is completely
  different to listening to the voices whilst watching (for example)
  an animated character in a point 'n' click adventure.  Your disbelief
  isn't suspended whilst looking at a bunch of slider gadgets, but it
  might be whilst watching GuyBrush Threepwood.  If you can - visualize
  the voice's intended purpose - and then click on 'Speak'.

  @{fg shine}"()"@{fg text}
  You can use brackets around words to make them stand out from the rest
  of the sentence.

  Another feature of brackets is the following:

    (that) is the kweh-stion.

    that - is the kweh-stion.

  although the word 'that' is spoken exactly the same way, in both
  instances, the word 'question' is spoken differently.  You usually
  discover thise things by accident.

  @{fg shine}"-"@{fg text}
  You can use hyphens, either: to join words together, like-so; or to
  put a longer pause betwen them, like - so.

  You can also use them to stress a particular word in a sentence, in
  order to change it's overall meaning.  The general rule is, the first
  word in a string joined together with hypens, will be stressed:

    I am-a-speaking-clock.

  will stress the word 'am', make the sentence sound like an assertion,
  whereas

    I am a speaking-clock.

  would stress the word 'speaking,' making the sentence sound like an
  explanation of the clock's distinctive feature.

  @{fg shine}", ."@{fg text}
  The comma and full stop can be used to affect the way that a word
  is stressed.  The comma will generally make the word before it,
  RISE, and the full-stop will generally make it FALL.  You can also
  achieve a different sound on the last word, by NOT putting a comma
  OR a full-stop.

    tick, tock. tick, tock.

  would be intoned correctly.

  You can also, sometimes, dramatically affect the way that words are
  spoken, by ending a sentence with a longer version of the last word:

    don't u point @ me.
    don't u point @ meeee.

  would sound very different.

  @{fg shine}"numbers"@{fg text}
  Sentences can also sound different if numbers are used in place of
  words:

    out rai-juss-4-chune.

  sounds different to,

    out rai-juss-for-chune.

  @{fg shine}"letters"@{fg text}
  The same applies for letters that sound like words, such as:

    b c i j o p q r t u y.

  @{fg shine}"Concatenation"@{fg text}
  Sometimes, you can put two or more words together, to get them
  spoken more quickly,

    can'tcatch

  however, this won't always work, as some words end/begin with
  vowels, which will alter the sound when put together.

  @{fg shine}"mis-spelling"@{fg text}
  It is often best to deliberately mispell words in order to get them
  pronounced properly,

    kweh-stion

  So if you are doing a Monkey Island type game, you might need two
  versions of the data - one for displaying on screen, and one for
  speaking.

 @{fg shine}@{"I'll bear that in mind..." link MAIN}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node How
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  NOTE: I've gotten rid of the menus, and added pop-up menus that
  appear when you press and hold the right mouse-button.  What appears
  in these menus depends upon where the mouse is when you press it -
  the top-half of the screen is for the voices, and the bottom half is
  for the sentences.  This means that if you want to Load/Save voices,
  then you should have the mouse in the top half of the screen when
  you call the menu.  Top-half means 'above' the 'Human' string gadget.
  And vice-versa for the sentences.  However, you can Quit/Export from
  anywhere.

