@node Export
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}EXPORTING@{fg text}

  You can save the files as ready-made data statements.  All currently
  loaded voices and sentences will be included in the output, so if you
  only want to export the voices, or the phrases, simply "New" the ones
  that you don't want exporting.

  When you choose "Export" from the menu, a window will appear with a
  number of checkboxes, and a GTMX gadget (radio buttons) in it.

  The checkboxes represent the features of Amiga speech, and you can
  disable/enable them according to which features you will be using in
  your program.  That way, the data statements will only contain the
  information that you require.  The first column of checkboxes are for
  the V36 features, and you are most likely to not want the "volume"
  setting saving.  The second column contains the V37 stuff.  If you don't
  have V37 of the tranlator. library, then the second column will not appear.

  The GTMX gadget enables you to choose whether you want to export just
  the human versions of the sentences; just the translated versions; or
  both versions.

  Disable/enable as required, and then click on "Export" or "Cancel," at
  which point, a file-requester will appear.

  A rough guide to this file-format is:

  --------------START--------------
  ;reminder of settings saved
  data.b # of voices
  ;voicename
  data.w setting,setting,setting...
  ;voicename
  data.w setting,setting,setting...
  ;etc
  data.w etc,etc,etc...


  data.b # of phrases
  data$ "human phrase 1"
  data$ "translated phrase 1"
  data$ "etc..."
  ---------------END---------------

  You can now, simply load this file into an editor.  See @{"File-formats" link Files}
  for more detailed information on Exported files.  This will also tell
  you the structure of .voice and .phrase files, in case you don't want
  to use data statements in your program.

  NOTE: you may need to change the 'type' for the '# of voices' and
        '# of phrases' from bytes to words in your main program, if you
        concatenate the files, or you'll get an overflow.

  NOTE: If you are using this in conjunction with Blitz-Basic, then TED
        will only allow upto 128 characters on a line, so bear this in
        mind when creating sentences.  The maximum length of a human
        sentence in Talk2Me is 100 - but the maximum for the translated
        version is 200 (to be on the safe side).

  NOTE: The narrator.device expects any translated strings passed to it
        to end with a space, followed by a chr$(0) (null character).
        When the sentences are exported, the two characters are deleted
        from the end of the sentence, as the null character will not
        appear in the Blitz Basic text editor, and the same is probably
        true for any other language.  So if you are using data statements
        of the translated strings, you'll need to create a string that is

         " "+chr$(0)

        and then add this to the sentences when you READ them from the
        data statements.

 @{fg shine}@{"So that's how I export files..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Voices
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}VOICES@{fg text}

  @{fg shine}Creating@{fg text}
  There is a listview on the left, where you should see the entry

    <new voice>

  Whenever you click on this, a blank item is added to the listview,
  and the new voice takes the settings that are currently shown in
  the various slider gadgets.

  This means that if you want to copy one voice setting, you can
  select the voice-preset from the listview, and then click on
  <new voice> - everything will be copied except for the name,
  which will be blank.

  The string gadget above the listview will now be enabled, and the
  textgadget to the right of this should now state "n of n" to indicate
  the current voice number.  You can now enter a name for the voice in the
  string gadget, which you can edit at any time, by selecting the voice and
  then clicking on the string gadget.

  If the <new voice> list item is at the bottom when you click on it, the
  listview will scroll-up one place, for your (and my) convenience.

  @{fg shine}Loading@{fg text}
  To load previously saved voices, move the mouse above the "Human" string
  gadget, and then press and hold the right mouse-button: a pop-up menu
  will appear.  Choose 'Load Voices'.  The file requester that appears
  will filter files that do not end with ".voices".

  @{fg shine}Saving@{fg text}
  To save the voices automatically to a previously loaded file, choose
  'Save Voices' from the menu.  This will overwrite the old file without
  asking.

  To save the voices to a new file, choose 'Save As Voices' - this
  will always provide a file requester.

  The screen's title bar will contain the names of the current filenames
  when files are saved or loaded.

  @{fg shine}Selecting@{fg text}
  To select a voice as the current voice, simply click on the voice
  name in the listview.  The gadget settings will be changed to reflect
  the settings of this record.

  If there is a checkmark in the "Auto" checkbox, and there is currently
  a sentence in the sentence gadget, then the sentence will be spoken by
  the newly-selected voice.  This is to enable you to quickly test the
  same sentence with different voices.

  @{fg shine}Deleting@{fg text}
  To delete a voice, highlight the voice's name in the listview, and
  then click delete - there is no undo.

  See @{"File-formats" link Files} for more information on Saved and Exported files.

 @{fg shine}@{"So they're the voices..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode


@node V36
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}V36 Settings@{fg text}

  To the right of the voices listview, in the centre of the screen, are
  the gadgets related to the V36 settings.

  Prior to V37, the only settings that you could alter for the voice
  were:

  @{fg shine}Rate@{fg text}        Words spoken per minute - 40-400.
  @{fg shine}Pitch@{fg text}       Pitch in hz - 65-350.
  @{fg shine}Volume@{fg text}      0-64
  @{fg shine}Mode@{fg text}        Natural, Robot, Manual (see below)
  @{fg shine}Sex@{fg text}         Male, Female
  @{fg shine}Frequency@{fg text}   5000-28000 a beep will be sounded if you try
              to enter an invalid amount

  MANUAL (Mode above)
  This option enables you to directly alter the translated version of
  your sentence.  You can put the digits 0-9 after any vowel sounds,
  to state 'manually' how much stress should be placed on them - 0 being
  the lowest, and 9 the highest.

  So, "Hello." would be translated as

    /HEH4LOW.

  and you can change the 4 to another number or delete it, and you can
  add a digit afer OW - so

    /HEH4LOW7.

  sounds much better, as the OW sound is elongated.

  Please note that I got crashes when putting a 0 in the last word in a
  sentence, but this was for testing purposes, and I can see no point in
  using 0s anyway.  There is no way that the program can check the
  validity of your entries, so be careful.

  If there is a checkmark in the "Auto" checkbox, and there is a sentence
  in the string gadget, then the sentence will be spoken automatically
  when you let go of one of the above gadgets.  N.B. but if you lower the
  RATE to below 160, then the checkbox will become disabled, as it can take
  a long time to speak sentences with a low RATE, and there is presently
  no way I can flush the speech buffer from Blitz Basic.

  NOTE: When a 'Human' sentence is translated, the translated string has
  a space, and a null (0) character at the end.  The null character will
  not appear in the string gadget, but the space will.  DO NOT delete the
  space at the end of the translated sentence.

 @{fg shine}@{"That's V36 then..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node V37
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}V37 Settings@{fg text}

  If you don't have V37 of the translator.library, then the following
  gadgets will be disabled.

  To the far right, at the top of the screen, are the V37 gadgets, they
  are

  @{fg shine}Enthusiasm@{fg text}           Fun, fun, fun!
  @{fg shine}Perturb@{fg text}              Even more fun!

  @{fg shine}Frequency Adjust 1@{fg text}   Although you can adjust these, their
  @{fg shine}Frequency Adjust 2@{fg text}   usefulness seems dubious - my attempts
  @{fg shine}Frequency Adjust 3@{fg text}   made the speakers buzz - but that may
                       have been because I was using such
  @{fg shine}Amplitude Adjust 1@{fg text}   a high frequency setting in the V36
  @{fg shine}Amplitude Adjust 2@{fg text}   gadgets - and changing the voice to
  @{fg shine}Amplitude Adjust 3@{fg text}   MALE helps as well.  You can get some
                       interesting sounds with negative values.

  @{fg shine}Articulation@{fg text}         Seems to affect how well the words are
                       spoken.

  @{fg shine}Centphon@{fg text}             If this is zero, then the radio-buttons
                       on the far right of the screen will have
                       no effect - otherwise, all words spoken
                       will 'centralize' from the vowel sounds
                       in the words, towards the selected vowel
                       sound in the radio buttons.  The best way
                       to understand, is to try a sentence with
                       Cent: on zero, and then on max.  Can make
                       voices sound like Melvyn Bragg, or
                       Inspector Clueseau - or like you're
                       pinching your nose with thumb and
                       forefinger, or you've got your mouth full.

  @{fg shine}AV bias@{fg text}              As with frequency and amplitude above
  @{fg shine}AF bias@{fg text}              tends to make my speakers buzz, but you
                       might discover a use for them.

  If there is a checkmark in the "Auto" checkbox, and there is a current
  sentence, then the sentence will be spoken automatically when you let
  go of one of the above gadgets - unless you click on a radio button
  when the "Cent:" slider is set to zero - as this turns off the radio
  buttons.  The sentence will be spoken in the current voice if there is
  one, otherwise in the default voice.

 @{fg shine}@{"That's V37 then..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode

@node Phrases
@title "TALK2ME v1.21"

  @{fg shine}PHRASES@{fg text}

  @{fg shine}Creating@{fg text}
  There is a large list view, with the entry

    <new phrase>

  When you click on this, a new item will be added to the listview - if
  it is the first phrase, then it will be blank - if it is not the first,
  then it will copy the phrase from the currently highlighted listitem.

  There are two string gadgets above this listview: 'Human' and 'Trans'

  HUMAN: This is where you type your sentence in (it's called human, and
  not English, as this program could be used for other languages).  When
  your press [RETURN] in this gadget, it will be translated, and the
  translated version will be placed in the 'TRANS:' string gadget.  If
  the 'auto' checkbox is checked, then the sentence will be spoken.  The
  HUMAN string gadget will be enabled again, so that you can quickly edit
  sentences to get them sounding right.  The length of this string is now
  shown at the end of the string gadget.

  TRANS: Note: for this gadget to have any effect, you need to have the
  'Mode' cycle gadget set to 'Manual.'  You can edit the translated string,
  in order to get the exact stress that you want.  The digits 0-9 are placed
  after vowel sounds to state how they should be stressed - 0 being low
  stress, and 9 being high.  No checks are made as to the validity of your
  input, so make sure any digits you enter are after vowel sounds, like EH.
  The translated version will already have digits in, and you can safely
  alter these values, but you can also put digits after vowel sounds that
  don't presently have values after them.  When you press [RETURN], the
  sentence will be spoken in the current voice, or the default voice if
  there isn't a current voice.  The TRANS gadget will be enabled again, to
  allow you to quickly edit the translated string.  The length of this
  string is now shown at the end of the string gadget - please note that
  the length includes the trailing 'space' and a null character.

  Please be careful with your input into the Trans string gadget, as there
  is no way to check it for validity, and I got crashes if I put a 0 in
  the last word in a sentence - though this was for testing purposes, and
  there is no real reason to use 0s.

  The current phrase number will be shown in a text gadget to the right
  of the listview.

  If you want to copy a phrase (because you want to keep the current
  version, but want to try a few changes) you can click on the phrase
  that you want to copy, and then click on <new phrase> - the new
  phrase will contain the same sentence.

  @{fg shine}Translating@{fg text}
  There are 3 ways to get the current human sentence translated.

    1. press [RETURN] in the HUMAN string gadget.
    2. click the 'Translate' button.
    3. shift-delete everything in the TRANS string gadget,
       and then press [RETURN].

  @{fg shine}Loading@{fg text}
  To load previously saved phrases, move the mouse to the bottom half
  of the screen, press and hold the right mouse-button, and then
  choose 'Load Phrases' from the menu.  The file requester that appears
  will filter files that do not end with ".phrases".

  @{fg shine}Saving@{fg text}
  To save the phrases automatically to a previously loaded file, choose
  'Save Phrases' from the menu.  This will overwrite the old file without
  asking.

  To save the phrases to a new file, choose 'Save As Phrases' - this
  will always provide a file requester.

  NOTE: the screen's title bar will contain the names of the current
  filenames when files are saved or loaded.

  @{fg shine}Selecting@{fg text}
  To select a phrase as the current phrase, simply click on the phrase
  in the listview.  The sentence string gadget will now contain this
  phrase.

  If there is a checkmark in the "Auto" checkbox, then the newly-selected
  phrase will be spoken - in the current voice, if there is one, otherwise
  in the default voice.  This is to enable you to quickly test different
  sentences with the same voice.

  @{fg shine}Searching@{fg text}
  Type the 'search text' in the Search-Text string gadget - when you press
  return, the program will search the phrases (forwards from the current
  phrase) for any occurrence of the string.  If an occurrence is found,
  the 'search string' will be spoken, the relevant phrase will be high-
  lighted in the listview, and the phrase copied to the sentence gadget.
  If the 'search string' is not found, then the program will speak

    "I can't find it."

  To search again, after a 'successful find,' click on the '>' gadget to
  the right of the search string gadget, to find the next occurrence, if
  any.

  @{fg shine}Deleting@{fg text}
  To delete a phrase, highlight the sentence in the listview, and
  then click delete - there is no undo.  On a PAL machine, the delete
  button is at the bottom of the screen, but on an NTSC machine it is
  just below the Search-string gadget - so NTSC users should take care
  not to press it by mistake.

  See @{"File-formats" link Files} for more information on Saved and Exported files.

 @{fg shine}@{"They're the phrases then..." link How}@{fg text}
@endnode


